# Decide the Observer Runtime and Trigger Topology

## Step

Per-machine observers over local captures vs one central observer on flagg
over synced/indexed sessions (Typesense already sees them)? Trigger policy:
token thresholds (Mastra: ~30k message tokens, async buffered) vs cadence
(hourly? per-session-close via herdr-pings/session hooks)? Runtime: Inngest
durable function (house pattern, 110+ exist) vs launchd? Token budget per
day and which model via pi. Cursor semantics so only new material distills —
efficiency is a charter requirement.

## Grilling notes (2026-07-12, in progress)

- **Working direction (Joel + evidence)**: flagg-central observer session
  using pi with the `ds4-central` provider — DeepSeek V4 Flash served
  LOCALLY by `com.joelclaw.central.ds4.plist`, a Central LaunchDaemon
  (`/Users/Shared/joelclaw/opt/ds4/current/ds4-server`, :8000, ctx 100k,
  kv-disk cache, up since 2026-06-17 under the joelclaw service account —
  already durable infrastructure alongside postgres/redis/typesense/inngest).
  Zero marginal cost → observer can run continuously; transcripts never
  leave flagg for inference (input to the redaction ticket: the boundary
  moves to persistence).
- 100k ctx < session sizes → observer works map-reduce over indexed
  run_chunks deltas (~2M tokens/day per coverage research), not whole
  transcripts.
- Quality gate: prototype runs the same day through ds4-local AND the
  frontier model — pi with gpt-5.6-terra (Joel-named); side-by-side pages decide the default. Frontier likely
  reserved for the reflector regardless.
- Defect found en route: `joelclaw sessions search` ssh-targets the stale
  `dark-wizard` hostname and fails fleet-wide — needs a fix (flagg rename
  fallout).

## Resolution (2026-07-12, grilled with Joel)

1. **Placement**: flagg-central. Observes Pi+Claude on flagg+blaine (the
   proven-capture core per coverage research); codex joins when its delivery
   ticket closes; panda ignored (decommissioning).
2. **Runtime shape (Joel's charter)**: a **headless herdr session** — a
   persistent pi observer session managed by the herdr server, so it can
   SPAWN observable, interactive sub-agents in panes Joel can drop in on.
   The observer of the fleet is itself observable. Not an Inngest batch
   function: the loop is a living session; Inngest/launchd play supervisor.
3. **Durability** (voice-map doctrine imported — silent drift is the enemy):
   a supervisor canary (launchd/executor cron) ensures the observer session
   exists and respawns it if missing; distillation cursor persisted (file or
   Typesense) so restarts resume idempotently; the ds4 dependency is already
   durable (`com.joelclaw.central.ds4.plist`, up since 2026-06-17).
4. **Models**: pi with `ds4-central` (DeepSeek V4 Flash, local :8000, ctx
   100k, zero cost) as default distiller — transcripts never leave flagg for
   inference. `gpt-5.6-terra` via pi as frontier comparator in the prototype
   and presumptive reflector model.
5. **Trigger/efficiency**: continuous self-paced loop over indexed
   run_chunks deltas (~2M tokens/day), map-reduce within 100k ctx; local
   inference makes rationing unnecessary.

Cadence fine-tuning and the supervisor script are prototype-ticket work.

## Amendment (2026-07-12, Joel, mid-prototype)

**Default distiller is pi with `gpt-5.6-terra`, not the local model.**
Prototype measurement decided it: ds4-central ran ~546s per batch (~9 min) —
fine in theory for a background loop, unacceptable as the fleet's memory
latency in practice ("we need to use pi with gpt-5.6-terra, we can['t] use
local model for this lol"). ds4-central keeps the cheap high-volume side
jobs where latency doesn't matter and judgment is shallow: noise-bar
classification, sensitive-domain flagging, batch pre-filters. Terra writes
the observation prose.

Privacy note, honestly: with terra, session content transits the provider at
distillation time. This adds no new exposure class — the transcripts were
produced in provider conversations to begin with — and the redaction
resolution's enforcement point was always persistence, not inference. The
cross-provider wrinkle (Claude transcripts distilled via an OpenAI-family
model) is noted and accepted.

## Amendment 2 (2026-07-12, Joel — final architecture)

Three tiers, all inside herdr:

1. **Orchestrator/gateway/monitor**: a dedicated DURABLE headless herdr
   session running pi with **gpt-5.6-sol at medium effort** — long-lived,
   cheap, never does the heavy lifting. It watches the capture stream,
   maintains the cursor, applies the noise bar, batches work, spawns and
   steers worker panes, harvests their results, writes pages + the daily
   index, and reports. The supervisor canary (Amendment/Resolution §3)
   keeps THIS session alive.
2. **Distillation workers**: **gpt-5.6-terra** pi agents in herdr panes the
   orchestrator commands — observable, interactive, droppable-in-on (Joel's
   requirement). Terra writes the observation prose.
3. **ds4-central as needed**: cheap local classify/pre-filter calls
   (noise bar, sensitive-domain flags) issued by the orchestrator.

Steering machinery already exists and is proven: herdr pane split/run,
callsigns, herdr-pings turn events, `herdr-ping-wait` wake loop — the
orchestrator uses the same loop the steering session used to run today's
renderer/coverage/prototype workers. Today was the live rehearsal of this
exact pattern.

## Amendment 3 (2026-07-12, Joel — extension identity + cache-aware turns)

1. **The observer is an activated pi EXTENSION, not a kickoff prompt.** The
   charter injects into the SYSTEM PROMPT via an extension (pattern:
   existing extensions like memory-capture), activated for the observer
   session. Why it matters: a kickoff prompt is just the first user message
   — compaction eventually summarizes it away and the daemon drifts from
   its own constitution. System-prompt identity survives every turn and
   every compaction, and restart becomes `pi` + extension activation, no
   fragile prompt string (today's migration proved kickoff-restart is
   brittle).
2. **Cache-aware turn design.** With a stable system-prompt prefix, every
   tick rides the provider prompt cache. Consequences to build in:
   - Maximize the stable prefix (charter + tool config fixed; nothing
     dynamic above the fold).
   - Tick cadence considered against provider cache TTL — batch work per
     tick to amortize cold prefixes rather than many tiny warm-up turns.
   - **Daily session rotation**: identity lives in the extension, state
     lives in the cursor file + observation pages — so the session itself
     is disposable. Rotate fresh each morning: bounded context, no
     compaction debt, clean cache.
   - Tick reports stay one line; worker panes carry the heavy tokens
     (already chartered) — the orchestrator's context is a ledger, not a
     warehouse.

Graduates: build-observer-pi-extension.
